text: I actually think this will be better than the previous iterations. The previous Americanized remake tried too hard to pay homage to the original without actually doing anything original itself. You don't do an American remake of a Japanese horror film and keep the locale and setting in Japan. Here's how it works. The Japanese originals create the overall plot and originality of the storyline; the Japanese are usually best at this (for supernatural ghost stories). The American studios then pay the original storywriters some hefty royalties (out of both respect and legal obligations) and do what the American studios do better - make the monsters, ghosts, and overall setting scarier or more cinematic (depending on the needs of the storyline). They usually have the creative freedom to move the storyline's central locale - something they failed to do in the first Americanized remake of Ju-On. One glance at this and I can already see this is light years ahead of the original American remake in the special effects department, and the original American remake was already light years ahead of Ju-On in that area. But this time they also look like they finally moved the setting to something more suited to American audiences (it looks like Washington, Minnesota, or maybe even Canada). Horror films pretty much all still suffer from the same problems - weak plot points in which the screenwriters overly rely on the stupidity of the characters in their story. That aspect won't change here. But it does appear to be something that will actually be an improvement over the original Americanized remake.

text: During the panel, Raimi said, ‚ÄúSometimes you need to destroy the original and move on. You have to move on while paying tribute to it, and nod to the audience while paving a new way, which is what Nicolas has done with this film.‚Äù       For many, it may feel like only yesterday that the Japanese horror craze had a foothold in the business of frightening audiences with raven-haired evil forces. Shockingly though, we are closing in on 20 years since the heyday of the original Japanese films and subsequent American remakes of¬†The Ring¬†and¬†The Grudge. Now¬†Sam Raimi¬†(of¬†The Evil Deadand classic¬†Spider-Man¬†movies) is back again with his Ghost House Pictures production company to produce an all-new¬†The Grudge¬†that will kick 2020 off in style. With Director Nicolas Pesce (The Eyes of My Mother, Piercing) and stars Andrea Risebourough, Lin Shaye, and¬†GLOW's Betty Gilpin¬†by his side, Raimi bought the first   The first big takeaway is that we shouldn't be mistaken, this new film is not necessarily a reboot and it isn‚Äôt necessarily a sequel. Instead it is another tale from the same universe as the Japanese films, as well as the American ones. ‚ÄúThe Grudge¬†is an anthology series,‚Äù Pesce explains. ‚ÄúThe movies are [about] different characters, different stories, different locations, different ghosts. Aside from the second and third American remakes, it‚Äôs all been very contained to Japan.‚Äù  While the characters from the original American remake were primarily foreigners living in and around Tokyo, this new version will take place wholly in the U.S. Pesce says, ‚ÄúThe Grudge is like a virus; it‚Äôs super-contagious. So the fact that it would stay in the tiny city of Tokyo is unrealistic. It exists in Asia, Europe, Africa, in America, because it has spread. I know a lot of people think this is a remake of a remake, which is isn‚Äôt‚Ä¶ this movie exists in the same world as the Japense movie, we‚Äôre just adding a chapter.‚Äù

text: When will Hollywood stop showing all the scary stuff in their trailers for horror films? You basically give away most of the best stuff and show way too much. You should be showing one long scene that's creepy and tense, and then maybe give away a scare if you feel you need to. Then show a few shots of creepy images that don't give away anything major like, you know, several deaths like this trailer does.   But I guess when your goal is to get a bunch of dumb teenagers into the theatre so they can get startled at loud noises and things jumping out, the trailer promises that. Problem is that if you give away a bunch of jump scares and that's all your film has, then it's not worth seeing.

text: No one beats the very first version of this horror movie. I remember watching it while my family moved in Japan late 2002, I was 7 at the time. The director was Takashi Shimizu and the title was ‚ÄòJu-On The Grudge‚Äô. I remember almost shitting my pants when I first watched it and I couldn‚Äôt sleep at night often. That horror movie became VERY popular that every Halloween women always dressed as that super creepy little boy from the first version. If I‚Äôm not mistaken the girl in white dress with a very long hair in front of her face became well known in the part 2 of that movie. Since then this movie had a lot of versions from different countries specially America or the Hollywood version. If I‚Äôm not mistaken, my grandma said Takashi Shimizu co-directed the very first The Ring movie which was also originally a Japanese horror movie. Oooooh I don‚Äôt want to see those movies ever again lol. Japanese directors makes one of the best horror movies, in my opinion.

text: I.....really don't know how I feel about this. I like the director behind it, but I'm fed up with remakes of foreign movies, especially Japanese. I just don't see how it's effective to take a dread inducing, eerie film like The Grudge and give it the Hollywood treatment of jumpscares, jumpscares, and more jumpscares. The entire reason the original American one worked is because it had the exact same director as the Japanese one.  I can't really say anything definitive until I actually see the movie, but I can say that, if they don't keep an ending in the same vein as the original, I'd honestly be disappointed. People don't just "find a way to end the curse". It doesn't end. Kind of like Hollywood.

The American ones was made in 2004 by The same director of the Japanese ones and produced by Sam Raimi (who produce this movie too), in 2006 had a Sequel and in 2009 were released the third part with another director, were the Saga was "Finished" and now this gonna be rebooted too

text: The main problem with this remake is once again stripping all of the Japanese culture. It is what made it unique. Traditional Japanese ghosts (or yurei) are characterized by their hair... where the long hair almost has a soul of it's own. The idea of a grudge being so strong that it manifests itself into a lingering, vengeful spirit is iconic to Japanese folklore. I wish American Horror films weren't so afraid of embracing the horror and stories of other cultures... especially when there is so much reference material! Are they afraid that we're so dumb that we wouldn't get it?

text: Here is the thing....  The whole filming in this movie is all wrong and the scenery needs work.   It is filmed very poorly and needs a better camera crew..  The actors are ok, but the random jump scares and lame effects makes this movie look low budget.  Compare this movie to all the other grudge movies.  They are all scary , except this one ...   It's like the people who created this movie didn't even bother watching the other grudge movies.   Every other grudge movie is scary with great filming methods and little Cgi.     Horror movies are supposed have a slow story line and filmed slowly with great scenery methods and little Cgi as possible. This movie was fast and all over the place.  Guess the cameraman and effects crew fucked up in this movie.  This movie has nothing to do with the other grudge movies and it's really low budget due to all the Cgi , random jump scares, bad scenery and poor camera methods.    Disappointed.  5 out of 10.  I only gave it 5 because the actors are good.  I remember renting the Grudge from Blockbuster in 2004 on VHS and watching it in my VCR (look that up kids)....I was actually entertained/scared and I became a fan of the grudge  It's 2020 and all your cgi and technology still can't beat the 2004 version grudge when it was on VHS?  Come on guys, this is exactly whats wrong with movies today.  We need someone like James Wan to fix this lame movie lmao.
